			h2 Notice
			p Be wary that some of the following sections apply for real-life use only and have for the sole purpose of being informative to those curious enough to take this online game to the board. 
			p Bob and Alice are two fictional characters that will help you understand how the game is played.
			h2 Objective
			p Each player is responsible to his king's safety. The player who wins furigoma plays first. During each turn, a player may either move a piece that is currently on the board (and potentially promote it, capture an opposing piece, or both) or else drop a piece that has been previously captured. The game ends when a king is attacked and cannot make a legal move. This is what is known as checkmate: the king is captured which means the player responsible for that piece has failed to protect it and thus loses.
			h2 Player and Role Arrangement 
			p In shogi, pieces look alike. So how can we tell pieces apart? Orientation. A piece that belongs to you will be pointing towards your opponent and his pieces will be pointing towards you. Who starts to move? The player who starts is decided through a process called furigoma or 振り駒. Furigoma is when Bob or Alice toss five pawns. If the the number of promoted pawns facing up is higher than unpromoted pawns, then the player who tossed the pawns plays first. If they decide to play another game then they alternate turns as who plays first. The other pieces on the board are there to keep the king safe and capture the opponent king. Let us now see how to set the pieces on the board.
